      <hedline>
        <hl1>Solstice of Sweat</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Ann R Mesnikoff (Sierra Club) replies to William Safire's Dec 20 column satirizing global warming</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>S.U.V.-supporting William Safire satirizes the science of global warming (''Whither the Weather?,'' column, Dec. 20). Scientists say ceasing the spewing of carbon dioxide can slow the sizzling of the earth. Such sound solutions as gas-sipping cars, solar cells and efficient light bulbs (alliteration isn't everything) can stave off serious suffering.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>S.U.V.-supporting William Safire satirizes the science of global warming (''Whither the Weather?,'' column, Dec. 20). Scientists say ceasing the spewing of carbon dioxide can slow the sizzling of the earth. Such sound solutions as gas-sipping cars, solar cells and efficient light bulbs (alliteration isn't everything) can stave off serious suffering.</p>
        <p>Celebrating the solstice with strange, sunny summer days should signal something's askew.</p>
        <p>ANN R. MESNIKOFF  Washington Representative  Global Warming and Energy Program, Sierra Club  Washington, Dec. 20, 2001</p>
      </block>
